Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.12,0:00:04.09,Default,,0,0,0,,There are many exciting things happening\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.09,0:00:06.16,Default,,0,0,0,,in Jehovah’s organization.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.16,0:00:08.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Why, month after month, we read articles,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.69,0:00:12.13,Default,,0,0,0,,watch videos, and hear personal experiences\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.13,0:00:15.77,Default,,0,0,0,,about our brothers and sisters \Nwho are doing more for Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:15.77,0:00:19.17,Default,,0,0,0,,They are serving where \Nthe need is greater or reaching out \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.17,0:00:21.77,Default,,0,0,0,,for the School for Kingdom Evangelizers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.77,0:00:25.08,Default,,0,0,0,,They are working \Non construction, renovation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.08,0:00:29.15,Default,,0,0,0,,maintenance of Kingdom Halls, \Nor other theocratic projects. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.15,0:00:32.38,Default,,0,0,0,,No doubt, \Nmany of you watching this program \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.38,0:00:34.58,Default,,0,0,0,,are excitedly looking forward \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.58,0:00:37.79,Default,,0,0,0,,to expanding your ministry \Nin one of these areas. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.79,0:00:40.69,Default,,0,0,0,,We encourage you to do so. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.69,0:00:44.56,Default,,0,0,0,,You can be assured \Nthat you will receive much fulfillment \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.56,0:00:47.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and many blessings from Jehovah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.83,0:00:49.83,Default,,0,0,0,,On the other hand,  \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.83,0:00:52.27,Default,,0,0,0,,there are others \Nwho are watching this program\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.27,0:00:55.84,Default,,0,0,0,,who may feel discouraged \Nbecause their circumstances \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.84,0:01:00.48,Default,,0,0,0,,may seem to limit \Ntheir being as involved as they would like. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.48,0:01:03.08,Default,,0,0,0,,What are some of these circumstances? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.08,0:01:06.08,Default,,0,0,0,,These may include our age, our health, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.08,0:01:10.49,Default,,0,0,0,,our economic situation, \Nor our physical limitations. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.49,0:01:14.09,Default,,0,0,0,,For some of us, \Nperhaps our upbringing \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.09,0:01:17.13,Default,,0,0,0,,or past errors \Nwe have made in our life \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.13,0:01:20.40,Default,,0,0,0,,may cause us to feel \Nthat we are limited \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.40,0:01:23.30,Default,,0,0,0,,as to what we can do \Nfor Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.30,0:01:26.67,Default,,0,0,0,,As we know well, \Nfocusing on our limitations \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.67,0:01:29.61,Default,,0,0,0,,can affect our joy, \Ncausing discouragement. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.61,0:01:31.78,Default,,0,0,0,,What can we do?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.78,0:01:36.08,Default,,0,0,0,,There are many examples \Nin the Scriptures of men and women \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.08,0:01:38.92,Default,,0,0,0,,who had circumstances \Nbeyond their control \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.92,0:01:42.75,Default,,0,0,0,,that seemed to limit how much \Nthey could do for Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.75,0:01:47.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Others had to deal with the effects \Nof their upbringing and family life \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.42,0:01:50.59,Default,,0,0,0,,or with serious errors they made. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.59,0:01:53.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Did they allow themselves to be limited \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.60,0:01:56.63,Default,,0,0,0,,by their circumstances or their past? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.63,0:01:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,How did Jehovah feel about them? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.00,0:02:02.27,Default,,0,0,0,,How does Jehovah feel about us? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.27,0:02:06.41,Default,,0,0,0,,That is what we are going to discuss \Nin this month’s broadcast, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.41,0:02:07.81,Default,,0,0,0,,which has the theme \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.81,0:02:11.82,Default,,0,0,0,,“Are You Defined by Your Circumstances?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.82,0:02:13.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s start by looking at some \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.98,0:02:17.59,Default,,0,0,0,,who could have let \Ntheir circumstances limit them.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.59,0:02:22.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Consider first the example \Nof Joseph in the book of Genesis. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.33,0:02:25.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Joseph faced injustice at its worst. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.16,0:02:28.33,Default,,0,0,0,,His situation was especially hurtful \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.33,0:02:32.07,Default,,0,0,0,,since it was initially brought on by those \Nwho should have been closest to him\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.07,0:02:34.07,Default,,0,0,0,,—his family! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.07,0:02:37.17,Default,,0,0,0,,As a slave in Egypt \Nand later as a prisoner, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.17,0:02:40.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Joseph was indeed limited \Nin what he could do. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.71,0:02:44.05,Default,,0,0,0,,How might Joseph have reacted? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.05,0:02:47.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, \NJoseph could have become so preoccupied \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.05,0:02:49.19,Default,,0,0,0,,with what he could not do \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.19,0:02:52.19,Default,,0,0,0,,that he lost sight of what he could do.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.19,0:02:55.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Did Joseph let his circumstances \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.29,0:02:57.49,Default,,0,0,0,,paralyze his life? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.49,0:02:59.10,Default,,0,0,0,,No! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:59.10,0:03:01.93,Default,,0,0,0,,He chose to make \Nthe best of his situation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.93,0:03:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, \Nnote what Joseph did \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.00,0:03:06.50,Default,,0,0,0,,while serving as a slave \Nin Potiphar’s house \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.50,0:03:11.27,Default,,0,0,0,,if we turn together \Nto Genesis 39:4: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.27,0:03:14.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“Joseph kept finding favor in his eyes, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.78,0:03:17.61,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he became his personal attendant. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.61,0:03:20.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“So he appointed him over his house, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.05,0:03:23.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and he put him \Nin charge of all that was his.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.59,0:03:26.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Joseph worked diligently \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.19,0:03:29.36,Default,,0,0,0,,within the limitations \Nof his circumstances. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.36,0:03:31.63,Default,,0,0,0,,He took a similar approach while in prison. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.63,0:03:34.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Joseph focused on what he could do \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.70,0:03:38.50,Default,,0,0,0,,despite suffering the effects of injustice.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.50,0:03:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,As a second example, \Nconsider Hezekiah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.84,0:03:44.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Hezekiah is one \Nwho might easily have felt \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.87,0:03:48.11,Default,,0,0,0,,that he was defined by his upbringing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.11,0:03:52.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Look at the terrible example \Nthat was set by his father, Ahaz, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.85,0:03:56.92,Default,,0,0,0,,as recorded in 2 Kings chapter 16. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.92,0:03:59.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Second Kings chapter 16, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.56,0:04:03.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and notice what verse 3 says about Ahaz: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.63,0:04:08.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“Instead, he walked in the way \Nof the kings of Israel, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.20,0:04:12.37,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he even made his own son \Npass through the fire, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.37,0:04:15.81,Default,,0,0,0,,“following the detestable practices \Nof the nations \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.81,0:04:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah had driven out \Nfrom before the Israelites.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.74,0:04:23.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Hezekiah’s father did detestable things \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.61,0:04:25.75,Default,,0,0,0,,in opposition to Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.75,0:04:27.75,Default,,0,0,0,,But Hezekiah showed \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.75,0:04:29.85,Default,,0,0,0,,that he was not the helpless victim \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.85,0:04:31.89,Default,,0,0,0,,of a poor parental example. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.89,0:04:33.89,Default,,0,0,0,,What did he do? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.89,0:04:37.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, turn in your Bibles \Nto 2 Kings chapter 18 \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.76,0:04:39.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and notice verse 3, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.96,0:04:42.20,Default,,0,0,0,,what it says about Hezekiah: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.20,0:04:46.34,Default,,0,0,0,,“He kept doing what was right\Nin Jehovah’s eyes,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.34,0:04:50.14,Default,,0,0,0,,just as David his forefather\Nhad done.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.14,0:04:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Verse 5 says of Hezekiah: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.84,0:04:56.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“There was no one like him \Namong all the kings of Judah.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.91,0:04:59.22,Default,,0,0,0,,He became fully involved in true worship. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.22,0:05:02.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Verses 6 and 7 say that Hezekiah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.09,0:05:07.92,Default,,0,0,0,,‘held fast to Jehovah, \Nand Jehovah proved to be with him.’\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.92,0:05:12.33,Default,,0,0,0,,How encouraging \NHezekiah’s example is for us! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.33,0:05:14.76,Default,,0,0,0,,We can choose to be loyal to Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.76,0:05:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and do much in our worship of Jehovah, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.00,0:05:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,even if we did not grow up in a family \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.74,0:05:21.74,Default,,0,0,0,,that served Jehovah fully. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.74,0:05:25.88,Default,,0,0,0,,We are not helpless victims \Nof our environment. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.88,0:05:30.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Hezekiah’s example \Nreassures us that our past \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.15,0:05:33.32,Default,,0,0,0,,does not have to control our future.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.32,0:05:37.45,Default,,0,0,0,,As a third example, \Nconsider the apostle Paul. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.45,0:05:39.92,Default,,0,0,0,,He did not let his own past mistakes \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.92,0:05:43.36,Default,,0,0,0,,involving religious prejudice and violence \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.36,0:05:46.33,Default,,0,0,0,,stop him from giving his all to Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.33,0:05:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,How did Paul feel about his past? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.00,0:05:55.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, let’s read together \Nat 1 Corinthians 15:9: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.64,0:05:59.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“For I am the least of the apostles, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.44,0:06:02.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“and I am not worthy \Nof being called an apostle, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.65,0:06:06.68,Default,,0,0,0,,because I persecuted \Nthe congregation of God.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.68,0:06:09.65,Default,,0,0,0,,“I am the least of the apostles.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.65,0:06:13.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Later, when writing to the Ephesians \Nas recorded at Ephesians 3:8, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.86,0:06:18.06,Default,,0,0,0,,he calls himself \N“less than the least of all holy ones.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.06,0:06:21.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, at 1 Timothy 1:15, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.63,0:06:25.64,Default,,0,0,0,,he now calls himself \Nthe “foremost” of all sinners. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.64,0:06:29.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, \NPaul’s prior treatment of the congregation \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.24,0:06:31.51,Default,,0,0,0,,weighed heavily upon him.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.51,0:06:35.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Could Paul have reasoned \Nthat he was damaged? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.28,0:06:37.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Could he have reasoned that his past \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.55,0:06:40.12,Default,,0,0,0,,limited what he could do for Jehovah? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.12,0:06:43.45,Default,,0,0,0,,He could have, \Nbut Paul did not do that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.45,0:06:46.32,Default,,0,0,0,,He poured himself out \Nfor the congregation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.32,0:06:49.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Why, Paul was privileged to write \Nmore books and letters \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.49,0:06:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,in the Christian Greek Scriptures \Nthan anyone else. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.03,0:06:55.63,Default,,0,0,0,,He demonstrated \Nan outstanding zeal for the ministry. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.63,0:06:59.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul did not let his conduct in the past \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.14,0:07:03.01,Default,,0,0,0,,dictate what he could do for Jehovah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.01,0:07:05.54,Default,,0,0,0,,And there are many other examples as well. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.54,0:07:10.11,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \Nare we in a difficult economic situation? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.11,0:07:12.75,Default,,0,0,0,,The account in 2 Corinthians chapter 8\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.75,0:07:14.92,Default,,0,0,0,,tells us about the Macedonians.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.92,0:07:18.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul says that they were in deep poverty. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.29,0:07:21.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet they begged to have a financial share\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.22,0:07:23.26,Default,,0,0,0,,in the relief work.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.26,0:07:25.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Are we older in years? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.60,0:07:27.60,Default,,0,0,0,,We may think of Anna. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.60,0:07:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The account at Luke 2:36-38\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.00,0:07:33.94,Default,,0,0,0,,tells us that she was 84 years old \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.94,0:07:35.94,Default,,0,0,0,,and that her husband had died\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.94,0:07:38.37,Default,,0,0,0,,after just seven years of marriage.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.37,0:07:40.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, \N“she was never missing from the temple.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.74,0:07:44.95,Default,,0,0,0,,She rendered\N‘sacred service day and night.’\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.95,0:07:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,What lessons do we learn \Nfrom these accounts? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.49,0:07:53.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Our dear brothers and sisters\Nin Bible times were just like us.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.39,0:07:57.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Many were in circumstances\Nthat they would not have chosen.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.29,0:08:00.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet,\Nthey did not let their circumstances\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.56,0:08:03.57,Default,,0,0,0,,or their past define them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.57,0:08:06.40,Default,,0,0,0,,They joyfully did what they could \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.40,0:08:09.11,Default,,0,0,0,,within the limits of their situation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.11,0:08:11.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And these are just a few examples. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.51,0:08:14.04,Default,,0,0,0,,There are many others in the Bible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.04,0:08:17.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Why not make it a personal study project \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.25,0:08:19.25,Default,,0,0,0,,to research faithful ones \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.25,0:08:22.25,Default,,0,0,0,,who were in circumstances \Nsimilar to yours? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.25,0:08:25.76,Default,,0,0,0,,How did they stay involved \Nin Jehovah’s work? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.76,0:08:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We are sure \Nthat you will be greatly encouraged.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.00,0:08:36.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, \Nwe’ve considered examples of those \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.67,0:08:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,who did not let \Ntheir circumstances hinder them \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.00,0:08:42.34,Default,,0,0,0,,from giving their all to Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.34,0:08:44.57,Default,,0,0,0,,But another question is: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.57,0:08:48.64,Default,,0,0,0,,How does Jehovah \Nview his faithful servants \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.64,0:08:50.98,Default,,0,0,0,,despite their limitations?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.98,0:08:54.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I’ve often thought \Nabout the example of John the Baptizer. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.48,0:08:59.19,Default,,0,0,0,,As we know, he was arrested \Nshortly after Jesus started his ministry. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.19,0:09:01.19,Default,,0,0,0,,John could have felt \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.19,0:09:05.43,Default,,0,0,0,,that he was no longer of use \Nto Jehovah or the work. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.43,0:09:09.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, as recorded at Matthew 11:11, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.33,0:09:11.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus said about John: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.50,0:09:13.77,Default,,0,0,0,,“Among those born of women, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.77,0:09:18.44,Default,,0,0,0,,there has not been raised up \Nanyone greater than John the Baptist.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.44,0:09:20.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s and Jesus’ view of John \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.68,0:09:23.28,Default,,0,0,0,,was not based \Non the man’s circumstances \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.28,0:09:25.41,Default,,0,0,0,,of being in prison. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.41,0:09:29.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Their view of John was based on\Nwho he was on the inside\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.49,0:09:32.26,Default,,0,0,0,,and on his relationship with Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.26,0:09:35.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah did not focus on the limitations. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.86,0:09:39.13,Default,,0,0,0,,In Jehovah’s eyes, \NJohn was great. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.13,0:09:42.93,Default,,0,0,0,,He was still a faithful servant \Ndoing the best that he could, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.93,0:09:46.20,Default,,0,0,0,,and that was all that really mattered.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.20,0:09:49.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Another example \Nthat may come to your mind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.04,0:09:51.07,Default,,0,0,0,,is that of King David. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.07,0:09:55.08,Default,,0,0,0,,As we know, \NKing David committed serious sins. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.08,0:09:57.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, \NDavid repented for his sins, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:57.58,0:10:01.48,Default,,0,0,0,,and there is no record\Nthat he repeated them.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.48,0:10:04.35,Default,,0,0,0,,How did Jehovah view him? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.35,0:10:07.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Did Jehovah see David as damaged, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:07.69,0:10:11.69,Default,,0,0,0,,as a man who would always be\Nlimited in serving him?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.69,0:10:16.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice Jehovah’s words \Ndirected to King Jeroboam \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.13,0:10:20.37,Default,,0,0,0,,at 1 Kings 14:8:\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.37,0:10:24.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“But you have not become \Nlike my servant David, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.71,0:10:26.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“who kept my commandments \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.71,0:10:29.58,Default,,0,0,0,,“and who walked after me \Nwith all his heart, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.58,0:10:32.75,Default,,0,0,0,,doing only what was right in my eyes.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.75,0:10:35.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah viewed David \Nas a special servant. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.62,0:10:38.12,Default,,0,0,0,,He says that he \N“kept my commandments.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.12,0:10:41.02,Default,,0,0,0,,He did \N“what was right in my eyes.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.02,0:10:44.46,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s what Jehovah remembered.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.46,0:10:47.03,Default,,0,0,0,,How encouraging that is for us! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.03,0:10:49.63,Default,,0,0,0,,If we have repented \Nof our past mistakes \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.63,0:10:53.17,Default,,0,0,0,,and set matters straight \Nto the best of our circumstances, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.17,0:10:58.21,Default,,0,0,0,,we too can be assured \Nthat Jehovah loves us dearly. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.21,0:11:03.91,Default,,0,0,0,,He appreciates whatever we can do \Nin our worship of him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.91,0:11:05.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what’s the point? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.92,0:11:09.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, our past \Nor our present circumstances \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.99,0:11:13.99,Default,,0,0,0,,do not define our value before Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.99,0:11:17.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Our Father loves us for who we are, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.23,0:11:19.23,Default,,0,0,0,,and he values our efforts \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.23,0:11:22.73,Default,,0,0,0,,as we do the best \Nthat we can to serve him.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.73,0:11:25.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Why do you think it is important \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:25.80,0:11:29.57,Default,,0,0,0,,that we strive to see ourselves \Nas Jehovah does? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.57,0:11:34.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Because we can weaken, \Ndiscourage, or limit ourselves \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.44,0:11:39.45,Default,,0,0,0,,if we see ourselves only \Nin the framework of our circumstances. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.45,0:11:43.45,Default,,0,0,0,,May we work hard not to do that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.45,0:11:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,What does Jehovah see \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.86,0:11:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,when he looks \Nat his faithful servants today? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.59,0:11:54.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, turn, please, \Nto 1 Samuel 16:7. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:54.60,0:11:57.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And the setting is \Nthat Samuel was about to go \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.17,0:11:59.17,Default,,0,0,0,,to anoint the next king of Israel; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.17,0:12:02.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and he goes to the house of Jesse; \Nand Jesse lines up all of his sons, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.61,0:12:05.11,Default,,0,0,0,,except for David,\Nwho is still out in the field; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.11,0:12:08.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and Samuel walks in \Nand he sees Eliab. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.84,0:12:11.35,Default,,0,0,0,,And based on what he sees, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.35,0:12:14.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Samuel concludes that this surely must be \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.08,0:12:16.15,Default,,0,0,0,,the next king of Israel. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.15,0:12:18.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet, note what Jehovah saw. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.85,0:12:23.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Please read with me 1 Samuel 16:7: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.86,0:12:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“But Jehovah said to Samuel: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.86,0:12:31.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Do not pay attention \Nto his appearance and how tall he is, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.40,0:12:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘for I have rejected him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.70,0:12:38.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘For the way man sees\Nis not the way God sees,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.44,0:12:41.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘because mere man sees\Nwhat appears to the eyes,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.98,0:12:45.25,Default,,0,0,0,,but Jehovah sees into the heart.’”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.25,0:12:48.38,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s the way Jehovah sees. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:48.38,0:12:51.39,Default,,0,0,0,,He does not look \Nat our outward appearance and our abilities; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:51.39,0:12:53.26,Default,,0,0,0,,he sees into our hearts. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.26,0:12:54.76,Default,,0,0,0,,He sees what we would be doing \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.76,0:12:57.49,Default,,0,0,0,,if all of the limitations \Nwere lifted off of us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.49,0:13:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Why, just the fact \Nthat we keep going, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.00,0:13:03.30,Default,,0,0,0,,that we keep putting \None foot in front of the other, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.30,0:13:06.47,Default,,0,0,0,,endears us to Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.47,0:13:09.31,Default,,0,0,0,,We understand the truth \Nof that statement, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.31,0:13:11.31,Default,,0,0,0,,and we all may agree \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.31,0:13:14.31,Default,,0,0,0,,that this is how \NJehovah views his people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.31,0:13:19.01,Default,,0,0,0,,However, we may have \Na hard time convincing ourselves \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.01,0:13:22.42,Default,,0,0,0,,if this really applies to me. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.42,0:13:26.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you ever wondered: \N‘Does Jehovah really see me? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.52,0:13:28.62,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Does he see what’s in my heart \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.62,0:13:32.19,Default,,0,0,0,,and value my desire to do more for him?’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.19,0:13:34.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The answer is yes. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.20,0:13:39.07,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, Jehovah has already seen \Nwhat is in your heart.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.07,0:13:41.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Think about this: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.40,0:13:44.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Why are you watching this program? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.61,0:13:47.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Why do you care about spiritual things? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.44,0:13:50.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Why are you, perhaps, \Nthe only one in your family \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.38,0:13:53.32,Default,,0,0,0,,who is a dedicated, \Nbaptized servant of Jehovah? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.32,0:13:56.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Or why are you, perhaps, \Nthe only one at your place of employment \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.89,0:14:00.89,Default,,0,0,0,,or the only one near where you live \Nwho’s serving Jehovah? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.89,0:14:03.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it because you are \Nso much more studious \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.49,0:14:05.79,Default,,0,0,0,,or smarter than everyone else? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.79,0:14:07.80,Default,,0,0,0,,No! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:07.80,0:14:10.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Haggai 2:7 tells us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.90,0:14:14.17,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah \N“will shake all the nations, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.17,0:14:17.97,Default,,0,0,0,,and the precious things \Nof all the nations will come in.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.97,0:14:21.51,Default,,0,0,0,,John 6:44 says \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.51,0:14:24.78,Default,,0,0,0,,that ‘no man can come to Jesus \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.78,0:14:28.38,Default,,0,0,0,,unless the Father draws him.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.38,0:14:32.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Jeremiah 31:3, Jehovah says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.79,0:14:36.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“I have loved you with an everlasting love. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.53,0:14:39.86,Default,,0,0,0,,That is why I have drawn you.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.86,0:14:43.77,Default,,0,0,0,,So again, why are you serving Jehovah? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.77,0:14:45.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Because Jehovah loves you. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.77,0:14:47.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah drew you. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.77,0:14:49.41,Default,,0,0,0,,As he was shaking the nations, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.41,0:14:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,he looked down into your heart \Nand he saw something very precious \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.04,0:14:55.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and he drew you to him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.21,0:14:57.78,Default,,0,0,0,,He said, \N“I want to draw this person to my Son. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.78,0:15:00.08,Default,,0,0,0,,“I want to draw this person to me. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.08,0:15:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I love this person.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.52,0:15:05.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah drew you, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.72,0:15:08.46,Default,,0,0,0,,not because you have\Nperfect circumstances,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.46,0:15:12.13,Default,,0,0,0,,but because of your heart\Nand because he loves you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.13,0:15:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He greatly appreciates \Nthat his servants give their best to him.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.80,0:15:25.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember, \Nnot the way man sees is the way God sees\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.27,0:15:27.84,Default,,0,0,0,,—Jehovah sees what the heart is. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.84,0:15:32.18,Default,,0,0,0,,May we work hard\Nto see ourselves as Jehovah does\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.18,0:15:35.78,Default,,0,0,0,,and be determined to never give up. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.78,0:15:40.19,Default,,0,0,0,,May we never forget that it is\Nthe privilege of bearing Jehovah’s name,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.19,0:15:42.26,Default,,0,0,0,,having a relationship with him, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.26,0:15:45.43,Default,,0,0,0,,and our love for Jehovah that defines us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.43,0:15:49.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah is happy \Nif we give the best that we can. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.83,0:15:52.10,Default,,0,0,0,,So may we do our part\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.10,0:15:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,by not limiting ourselves \Ndue to our circumstances,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.60,0:15:59.61,Default,,0,0,0,,but always look for ways \Nto give our best to Jehovah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:59.61,0:16:02.18,Default,,0,0,0,,You beautiful older ones, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.18,0:16:04.38,Default,,0,0,0,,even those with severe health problems, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.38,0:16:07.65,Default,,0,0,0,,can do much to help \Nin the great work that’s taking place today. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.65,0:16:09.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you may wonder \Nwhat can you do. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.99,0:16:11.99,Default,,0,0,0,,You can pray for your brothers and sisters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.99,0:16:13.66,Default,,0,0,0,,We need your prayers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.66,0:16:15.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Pray for the Governing Body. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.22,0:16:17.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Pray for those who are taking the lead. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.09,0:16:19.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Pray for the elders in your congregations. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.66,0:16:23.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Pray for those who \Nare going through difficult times. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.07,0:16:26.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Do such prayers help \Nthe work of the organization? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.74,0:16:28.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Absolutely! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.74,0:16:31.64,Default,,0,0,0,,James 5:16 tells us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.64,0:16:34.24,Default,,0,0,0,,that ‘a righteous person’s supplication \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.24,0:16:36.98,Default,,0,0,0,,has a powerful effect.’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.98,0:16:41.42,Default,,0,0,0,,No matter who we are \Nand whatever our situation in life, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.42,0:16:46.42,Default,,0,0,0,,may we find joy \Nin giving what we can for Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.42,0:16:50.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And may each one of us \Nrejoice at the privilege we have \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.53,0:16:54.41,Default,,0,0,0,,of being part of what Jehovah \Nis accomplishing in these last days.\N
